Not so fast Fred. There is no baby here. Just people who are unable and also unwilling to make a commitment to a business organization and to others. They're only concerned about their pay check and retirement. They don't understand technology. They don't care about the value of the customer (no customer, no revenue). They have never been held personally responsible for bad judgement and squandering good will. I successfully ran a business for 27 years by caring for the people who worked for me and for my customers. I came last. In this organization though, so many are responsible for so little without consequences that a new culture is needed. You can't spend the day arguing with people who can't hear. You can't waste time and money and put good people at risk when many others do nothing. Time is of the essence. Sometimes, like this situation, hard choices and immediate action is required. Losses must be staunched. Confidence must be regained and leadership must take place. Change is hard work. Good leadership is even harder work. Getting deadwood out of the way is paramount. No disrespect Fred, but strong leadership has no time for platitudes. In this case, protecting the business and going forward is the objective. It takes strength, courage and commitment to engage a new vision and a new culture. That is what I would instill.
