Jan. 20, 2014 11:30 p.m. ET
Enlarge Image
Avant-garde choreographer Sarah Michelson at 2012 Whitney Biennial.
Paula Court '4' Whitney Museum of American Art 945 Madison Ave. (212) 570-3600 Opens Friday whitney.org With "4," avant-garde choreographer Sarah Michelson
returns to the fourth-floor gallery of the Whitney Museum for the final installment of her "Devotion" series, which features commissioned texts by Richard Maxwell.
The series' first chapter, "Devotion Study #1—The American Dancer" had its premiere in the 2012 Biennial. It made waves in part because it was the first time the Biennial featured choreography, and in part because of the punishing, relentless nature of the piece, wherein the performers walked backward in circles for the greater part of 90 minutes. Many audience members were riveted. Some walked out. There's little to no "dancey-dance" in Ms. Michelson's work; instead she's interested in the legacy of modernism, and in compelling the watcher to think about the relationships between the choreographer, the work, and the style of performance. "4" occurs at 2 p.m., and seating is limited. 'WOW' BRIC Arts Media House 647 Fulton St. (718) 683-5600 Begins performances on Thursday bricartsmedia.org Girl, you know it's true! There's a Milli Vanilli opera in the works entitled, appropriately, "WOW." Lest you've forgotten Fab Morvan and Rob Pilatus's
chapter in pop culture history, the R&B duo won a Grammy award for Best New Artist in 1989, only to have it stripped when evidence emerged that the pair had not sung on their debut album. "WOW," presented at BRIC as a work-in-progress, is a collaboration between three well-regarded experimentalists: composer Joe Diebes,
poet Christian Hawkey, and director David Levine.
Their ambulatory, site-specific production takes place in a half dozen rooms in the 40,000-square-foot BRIC venue including a gallery, a black box theater and a rehearsal studio. The libretto borrows heavily from news conferences and interviews and examines labor exploitation, racism and other thorny aspects to the duo's rise and fall. LAST CHANCE: 'Parsons Dance' The Joyce Theater 175 Eighth Ave. (212) 242-0800 Through Sunday joyce.org Parsons Dance celebrates its 30th season this year. The program includes a world premiere, "The Introduction" set to Rubin Kodheli's
cello score. "Caught," a fan favorite, is also on the program. In the six minute long piece, a dancer makes more than 100 leaps but appears to be suspended in air thanks to impeccably timed lighting effects. Steven Vaughn
and Ian Spring
alternate performances. Created in 1982, it still wows. 'The Loneliness Of the Long Distance Runner' Enlarge Image
Sheldon Best, Malik Yoba and Zainab Jah in Alan Sillitoe's 'The Loneliness of the Long Distance Runner.'
Kevin Thomas Garcia Atlantic Stage 2 330 W. 16th St., (866) 811-4111 Opens tonight atlantictheater.org Colin, a disadvantaged teenager stuck in juvenile detention, finds escape in long distance running in Alan Sillitoe's
1959 short story, which became a 1962 film starring Tom Courtenay.
In its theatrical adaptation by Roy Williams,
the cast is predominantly black, and story is set just after the 2011 north London riots, which were sparked by the police shooting of an unarmed 29-year-old man, Mark Duggan,
and resulted in well over 3,000 arrests. The play had its premiere in September 2012 at the York Theatre Royal—it will be interesting to see if it has as much resonance for audiences in this new American production at the Atlantic. Sheldon Best, who plays Colin, is no stranger to athletic performances, having worked with the action/adventure theater ensemble, Vampire Cowboys. Leah C. Gardiner
directs.
